<TEXT>
nine members of a literary panel of the 
national endowment for the arts resigned to protest a new 
congressional edict that federally subsidized works must meet 
general standards of decency 
we deplore the implied threat of censure and attempt to 
constrict freedom of artistic expression and the rights grantd by 
the first amendment they wrote in a joint letter monday to nea 
chairman john e frohnmayer 
the nine resigned from an 11member nea panel of outside experts 
that judges grant applications from small independent presses 
literary magazines and nonprofit organizations that distribute 
contemporary literary works 
last year on the basis of the literary publishing panels 
recommendations frohnmayer approved 99 grants totaling 14 
million 
frohnmayer said resignations were premature and 
unfortunate he predicted the endowment would find a way to 
implement the new law in good faith without stifling artistic 
creativity 
the protest seemed largely symbolic nea spokesman josh dare 
said the panel was effectively dissolved when it completed its work 
on 198990 grant proposals last december a new panel minus the 
nine protesters will convene nov 26 to review next years 
grants 
the nine said they resigned over a new congressional requirement 
that the nea chairman shall ensure that grants are made 
taking into consideration general standards of decency and 
respect for the diverse beliefs and values of the american 
public 
congress tacked those restrictions onto the endowments current 
174 million budget shortly before it adjourned oct 28 the curbs 
replaced a much stricter obscenity ban that covered nea grants last 
year 
this year congress said only that obscenity shall not be 
funded by the nea and that obscenity judgments should be left to 
the courts 
even though the new curbs are milder than the former ban they 
nevertheless set a very scary precedent said jennifer moyer 
former chairwoman of the neas literary publishing panel if 
there are any restrictions on freedom of expression its 
unacceptable 
ms moyer a poet and literary publisher from mt kisco ny 
resigned along with eight others representing writers editors 
publishers booksellers and arts administrators on the panel 
in a separate letter informing frohnmayer of her resignation 
panelist helaine harris a bookseller from hyattsville md asked 
how the endowment can distinguish between decent or indecent 
art under the new law 
i feel that i can be a judge of artistic merit but i dont 
feel that i should pass judgment on decency she wrote i 
refuse to be a part of this selfcensorship process 
the other panelists who resigned were michael anania a poet 
fiction writer and teacher from chicago denise chavez a houston 
writer katharine harer of berkeley calif director of a 
distributing company for small literary presses brooks haxton a 
poet and teacher from white plains ny poet susan howe of 
guilford conn peter meinke a writer and director of a literary 
workshop at eckard college in st petersburg fla and e 
ethelbert miller a poet and teacher at howard university in 
washington dc 
the two panelists who did not resign were anne bourget of the 
california arts council in sacramento and beverly jarrett editor 
in chief of the university of missouri press at columbia mo 
ms jarrett who will serve on the newly formed literary 
publishing panel said she refused to resign because it seemed 
like throwing the baby out with the bath water at a time when the 
nea deserves support for helping the arts survive 
ms bourget did not return repeated telephone calls seeking her 
comment 
</TEXT>
