<TEXT>
the postal service is trying to pit worker 
against worker by offering cash bonuses but no hourly wage 
increases the president of the largest postal union contends 
its just a massage piece designed to divide us moe biller 
president of the american postal workers union said tuesday as 
thousands of unionized postal employees held a rally at a 
washington hotel 
the postal service and its four largest unions which together 
represent 660000 workers are in the midst of negotiations to 
replace contracts that expire nov 20 
biller called managements latest offer which has not been 
publicly outlined by the postal service a piece of garbage 
designed to pit worker against worker 
postal service spokesman michael west said we have negotiated 
at the table and not in the press at least for now we prefer 
to leave the specifics on the table 
biller said management had offered the 234000member national 
association of letter carriers a separate pay incentive plan aimed 
at dividing the two unions which bargain together although for 
separate contracts billers union represents 334000 postal 
clerks maintenance employees drivers and special delivery 
messengers 
assistant postmaster general david charters said the 
payincentive plan was part of the postal services goal of holding 
the rate of postage increases below the rate of inflation 
we think incentives to support that plan are in order 
charters said 
because the agency no longer subsidized by taxpayers must 
break even over time its board of governors has proposed raising 
the cost of mailing a letter from 25 cents to 30 cents next spring 
the unions have not made a counter offer biller declined to say 
how big a pay increases the unions were proposing or when the 
proposals would be presented letter carriers and clerks now 
receive a starting salary of around 24000 and can earn a maximum 
of about 31500 employees receive an additional 8560 in 
benefits and premium pay 
tuesdays solidarity rally attended by both letter carriers 
and clerks was aimed at showing the postal service that the two 
unions would stand together biller said 
two other unions also negotiating with the postal service are 
the national postal mail handlers union which represents 50000 
mail handlers and the national rural letter carriers association 
with about 42000 members 
biller said little progress had been made since the talks began 
in august he said he was not optimistic that a deal could be 
struck by next week 
right now i dont see anything on the horizon he said 
but postal service officials still have hope that an agreement 
will be reached by deadline west said 
under federal law it is illegl for postal workers to strike 
if a contract isnt reached by midnight nov 20 both sides could 
extend the current contract to give themselves more time to settle 
the dispute 
