<TEXT>
the white house and congress share blame for 
allowing scandal and mismanagement to go unchecked at the 
department of housing and urban development during the reagan 
administration a senate panel concludes 
in a report tuesday the investigative panel recommended a 
series of reforms including splitting up the white houses office 
of management and budget to create a separate office to monitor 
management of federal agencies 
hud mismanaged programs either because it opposed the program 
itself or because it lacked the capacity or leadership to 
operate them free from abuse the investigative subcommittee of 
the senate banking committee said unfortunately the various 
parties responsible for oversight were all negligent including hud 
itself omb and the congress 
sen bob graham dfla chairman of the panel appointed to 
handle the senates inquiry into the 2 billion hud scandals said 
the white house budget office under president reagan gave little 
scrutiny to required management reports and acted on none 
theres a need for more emphasis on the management side of 
omb graham said in an interview omb has become essentially a 
budget office they completely collapsed they became a filing 
agency not hardly reading and certainly not acting on the 
reports 
almost every safety net ripped and let hud crash to the 
ground he said 
the report blamed samuel pierce hud secretary for all eight 
years of reagans term for a handsoff management that fostered 
abuse it blamed congress for ignoring warnings of management 
problems and for holding no oversight hearings on the troubled 
department 
it said the senate failed in its confirmation responsibilities 
by allowing the reagan administration to fill the agencys top 
ranks with political appointees who had little interest in housing 
only two people nominated for hud positions during the 1980s failed 
to gain confirmation it said 
the panel recommended creation of a federal advisory panel to 
evaluate future hud political appointees and report to the senate 
on their worthiness graham compared it to the american bar 
associations review of judicial nominees which the senate 
considers before confirming judges and justices 
the senate panel focused on structural flaws that permitted the 
scandals a separate house investigation focused on personalities 
in the scandal and received far more public notice 
most of the subcommittees findings were approved unanimously 
the ranking republican sen connie mack rfla disagreed on 
splitting omb he also opposed creating the confirmation advisory 
board and the panels recommendation that huds staffing be 
increased 
graham said he would sponsor bills to implement the report 
congress created the white house budget office and could change it 
by law or the president could take executive action on his own he 
said 
among the panels other recommendations 
huds assistant secretary for administration should be a career 
employee not a political appointee hud should report to congress 
on other positions that should be reserved for career staff 
senate hearings should be held to receive each report of the 
hud inspector general the secretarys semiannual report and other 
required hud management reports 
hud should increase its monitoring of subsidy programs to 
eliminate excess subsidies for specific projects which were 
revealed in the hud scandals it should overhaul its calculation of 
fair market rents 
graham said he concluded the hud scandals were in part due to a 
deliberate effort by the reagan administration to fill the agency 
with people who werent competent and had antipathy for the 
departments mission resulting in failure and discredit falling 
upon housing programs 
the panel did not allege illegality but graham said he believed 
there may be some examples of perjury in reports pierce made to 
the president and congress on management capability as required by 
law 
the report cited a 1987 hud document stating that its financial 
management controls were adequate at the same time the report 
said hud management knew that serious problems existed with 
huds accounting systems and that the federal housing 
administrations accounting systems failed to meet accepted 
standards and were deemed unauditable 
pierce who is under investigation by the special prosecutor 
has denied any wrongdoing 
</TEXT>
