<TEXT>
a former civilian clerk at the quantico 
marine base will be sentenced jan 9 for killing a marine corporal 
in an attempt to hide her role in an alleged embezzlement scheme 
involving the helicopter squadron that serves president bush 
markeithia r reeves 24 of suitland md on tuesday entered a 
socalled alford plea in which a defendant does not admit guilt 
but acknowledges that the state has enough evidence to convict she 
faces a maximum sentence of 20 years to life in prison 
the plea was accepted just before reeves was to begin her 
firstdegree murder trial in the death of cpl estella pearson 
pearson 26 a quantico clerk whose responsibilities included 
reviewing travel vouchers was found shot to death march 5 in her 
car in a shopping center parking lot 
a second defendant tania t morton 23 of arlington va a 
former navy civilian clerk is scheduled to go on trial tuesday 
following reeves plea in prince william county circuit court 
prosecutors called two witnesses to the stand to substantiate the 
case against her 
according to testimony pearson was killed shortly after it 
became apparent that travel vouchers were being falsified involving 
members of the quanticobased helicopter squadron one which 
transports the president and other government officials 
secret service agent robert turner testified that 44 us 
treasury checks totaling 33000 with endorsements that had been 
forged had been traced to reeves and morton 
reeves worked in the same department as pearson and was 
responsible for preparing travel vouchers for employees going on 
temporary assignments 
turner said pearsons supervisor asked her to verify several 
suspicious travel vouchers markeithia saw this the agent told 
the washington post outside the courtroom then she started to 
realize they had caught on 
