<TEXT>
hundreds of american communities get drinking 
water from wells that contain unhealthy levels of pesticides and 
nitrates the environmental protection agency says 
a survey of 1347 wells in 50 states indicates that fewer than 1 
percent are contaminated from pesticides to levels that are of 
concern the epa said tuesday about 25 percent of the wells have 
nitrate levels considered worrisome the agency said 
nevertheless those wells provide drinking water for millions of 
people epa officials said 
while the vast majority of the countrys drinking water 
wells dont pose a risk to public health the findings provide an 
early warning sign that this needs to be taken seriously said 
henry habicht the epas deputy administrator 
environmentalists cited the survey as further proof that the 
nations groundwater is being contaminated by chemical runoffs from 
agriculture and other sources nitrates come largely from 
fertilizer and sewage 
ron phillips a spokesman for the fertilizer institute said the 
survey confirms that at least 96 percent of our groundwater is 
perfectly safe he disputed that the levels of nitrates found in 
some of the well water should be of concern 
the epa survey covered both private wells and wells that feed 
community water systems 
from the results of the survey the agency estimated that about 
104 percent of all community wells nationwide and 42 percent of 
private wells likely contain at least some pesticides the survey 
also indicated that more than half of the nations wells have water 
contaminated with nitrates from fertilizer sewage sludge or septic 
tanks 
although in most cases the contamination was at levels too low 
to be a health concern the epa said as many as 750 community water 
systems may have wells that have pesticide or nitrate contamination 
exceeding federal health guidelines it estimated that nearly 
80000 private wells in rural areas also likely have unhealthy 
levels of contamination 
many of the pesticides found in the drinking water are suspected 
of causing cancer or damage to vital organs if consumed at 
significant levels over a long period high levels of exposure to 
nitrates can cause blue baby syndrome in very young infants as 
well as other illnesses 
the epa survey reinforces existing strong evidence that 
nitrates are contaminating groundwater said justin ward of the 
natural resources defense council a washingtonbased environmental 
group 
the nrdc and other environmentalists however said the epa 
findings may understate the seriousness of the problem in some 
regions of the country where pesticides and nitrogen fertilizers 
are heavily used 
they criticized the epas use of national contamination 
estimates that include parts of the country where there are few 
pesticides or nitrates to contaminate wells 
the epas habicht said there likely are regional hot spots 
where a significantly higher percentage of wells are contaminated 
he said the epa planned to further examine the overall findings to 
focus on regional problem areas the agency provided no estimates 
on water contamination by regions or states 
the community water systems included in the survey ranged from 
those that provide drinking water to very small towns to others 
that serve densely populated urban areas including midsize and 
large cities 
many of the countrys largest cities rely on surface water for 
drinking rather than groundwater from wells 
the two most frequently detected pesticides found in the well 
water were dacthal a broadleaf weed killer used primarily on 
lawns and atrazine a widely used weed killer used in agriculture 
especially on corn and sorghum the epa said 
dacthal and nine other pesticides were found at low levels not 
considered a health threat but atrazine and five other pesticides 
including some that have been banned by the epa were found at 
levels considered a health concern 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

