<TEXT>
a newly released report alleges favoritism in 
the governments past handling of some shaky savings and loans but 
regulators havent decided whether to pursue the matter 
the document indicates that federal regulators gave preferential 
treatment as far back as the mid1980s to some ailing sampls whose 
executives sat on a regional regulatory board 
the report made public tuesday at a hearing by the house budget 
committees task force on urgent fiscal issues names several sampl 
executives who allegedly received favorable treatment from the 
federal home loan bank in dallas 
but regulators said they havent decided if they will take 
action against those executives or the federal sampl examiners who 
allegedly favored them 
this has come to us off the wall thomas mason a spokesman 
for the office of thrift supervision said of the new revelations 
mason said the ots the agency that took over sampl regulation 
from the federal home loan bank system has no idea at this 
point whether it will pursue action against the people involved 
at the hearing rep charles e schumer dny said the 
favoritism indicated by a 1988 government review of the dallas home 
loan bank discouraged bank examiners and slowed recognition of the 
magnitude of the sampl crisis 
sirens were sounding in the basement of the federal home loan 
bank board throughout 1988 but the regulators just plugged their 
ears said schumer who chairs the budget committee task force 
the task force released a summary of the 1988 review of the 
dallas bank board which was responsible for regulating sampls in 
texas louisiana arkansas mississippi and new mexico 
like home loan banks in other regions of the country the dallas 
institution was controlled by sampls that it both supervised and 
loaned money to 
the review of the dallas bank by an outside peer review team 
of government examiners indicated that senior federal sampl 
regulators knew losses were deliberately concealed by the thrifts 
with the approval of local examiners 
it also found conflicts of interest that resulted in 
preferential treatment for some sampl executives who also were 
directors of the dallas bank 
in one case local examiners removed an auditor who questioned 
the chairman of an arkansas sampl who was a director of the dallas 
bank according to the task force document mr godwin chairman 
of first federal savings of arkansas had been accused of 
defrauding shareholders 
the dallas bank board had been more interested in helping a 
fellow director than in removing godwin from his first federal 
post to protect shareholders the document said 
it said preferential treatment also apparently was given to 
allan d myers chairman of olney savings association and a 
director of the dallas bank shelby smith a director and former 
employee of the dallas bank robert mettlen a director of lamar 
savings association and a former director of the dallas bank and 
james ward chairman of commercial federal savings bank of 
louisiana and a director of the dallas bank 
the review found that the dallas bank failed to do financial 
examinations of nearly 200 sampls in a timely manner it said the 
dallas regulators delayed taking some supervisory actions and 
failed completely to take others 
it also accused the dallas bank board of 
terrible monitoring of sampls financial condition 
approving excessive pay and bonuses for sampl executives 
weak supervision and inflated financial ratings of sampls in the 
face of tremendous growth highrisk lending poor capital and 
insider abuse 
an overly bureaucratic multilayered decision process that 
slowed proper supervision 
another spokesman for the office of thrift supervision william 
fulwider declined to comment directly on those findings but said 
the system has improved greatly since sampl bailout legislation was 
enacted last year 
there has been a decided move to improve examination and 
supervision of sampls fulwider said he cited stricter capital 
requirements for sampls regulatory action against conflicts of 
interest and an increased number of federal examiners 
bailout legislation passed by congress last year to rescue the 
sampl industry could ultimately cost taxpayers 500 billion 
according to some estimates the legislation transferred regulation 
of sampls from the federal home loan bank system to the ots a new 
unit of the treasury department 
