<TEXT>
veronica iversen was an expert on how to stop 
smoking shed done it a halfdozen times 
but after a few days or the end of lent or her sisters 
hospitalization she always lit up again despite her vows and 
prayers 
finally she sought help from a source to which a small but 
growing number of heavy smokers are turning a doctor 
she chose elliot wineburg a psychiatrist at mount sinai medical 
school who specializes in treatment of stress about a third of his 
practice consists of heavy smokers who want to quit 
public education and antismoking classes have filtered out 
most of the people who can easily stop he said now were 
seeing the hard core people who are desperate and ashamed 
and who need medical attention 
a smoking problem is more than just a problem of will its an 
illness wineburg said curing it takes more than just say 
no you cant say that to an addict 
attention must be individual he argued since if you have a 
sore throat your internist doesnt say come to my lecture on 
penicillin along with 20 other people 
depending on the patient wineburg may prescribe three types of 
medicine nicotine gum antidepressant drugs or clonidine a drug 
usually used to control blood pressure 
in addition he uses techniques such as hypnosis biofeedback 
and cognitive therapy to help smokers relieve their underlying 
psychological problems 
within five weeks wineburg reports 68 percent of his patients 
stop smoking compared to a rate of 20 percent for many programs 
and courses 
wineburg treated iversen a single 68yearold retired 
secretary from brooklyn who was smoking a pack a day for 750 the 
fee was not covered by insurance because she was not suffering from 
an ailment caused by smoking 
on her first visit iversen insisted she didnt know why she 
smokes it was a bad habit with no purpose but after prodding 
she admitted to a very good reason if im tired it picks me up 
if im upset it calms me down 
iversen used nicotine to cope with everything from the drudgery 
of housekeeping to the illness of her sister who has alzheimers 
disease 
nothing is more difficult than being worried about someone and 
not being able to do anything about it she said 
at the beginning of her second visit iversen announced that 
shed smoked her last cigarette two hours earlier 
since nicotine is highly addictive wineburg needed to determine 
how much iversen had been ingesting told that she smoked a pack of 
true kings a day wineburg calculated that she consumed about eight 
milligrams daily 
he prescribed a daily dosage of four pieces of nicotine gum to 
ease the symptoms of nicotine withdrawal and showed iversen how to 
chew the gum slowly not swallowing the saliva until the nicotine 
could be absorbed through the cheek membrane 
during her third visit wineburg tested iversen and decided she 
would not be a good candidate for deep hypnosis he then showed her 
a way to relax her body from the toes up as he did so he tried to 
shore up her selfconfidence insisting you are a very strong 
person he concluded by saying im going home with you and 
handing her a cassette recording of their session 
the following week iversen talked about the times she is tempted 
to smoke and things she associates with smoking such as an 
occasional whiskey sour before dinner youll always want to 
smoke wineburg told her you cant get it out of your head 
the trick he said is to know how to resist 
on her fifth visit a therapist attached iversen to a machine 
that recorded the tension in her forehead muscles as she watched a 
video screen she learned ways to relax those muscles in moments of 
stress and tension she also learned a technique of deep breathing 
that reduces stress 
that was april 19 1989 since then veronica iversen has not 
smoked she no longer gets scowls from other members of her church 
group she has taken up oil painting to occupy her hands and mind 
and sometimes she would just love a cigarette 
</TEXT>
