<TEXT>
after nearly five years out of office former 
defense secretary michael heseltine is a more dominant national 
figure now than when he stormed out of margaret thatchers cabinet 
that reflects both a flair for the dramatic and the patience to 
wait for the prime minister to stumble 
tall and handsome with flowing blond hair and piercing blue 
eyes the 57yearold heseltine is a selfmade millionaire who 
doesnt quite fit any faction of the governing conservative party 
to admirers in the party heseltine looks like a savior 
critics accuse him of volatility and showmanship as his 
challenge to her leadership loomed thatcher aides commented all 
glamour and no substance 
he has carried the nickname of tarzan since 1976 when he 
grabbed the heavy ceremonial mace in the house of commons and swung 
it over his head at labor party leftwingers who were singing their 
anthem the red flag 
as defense secretary from 1983 to 1986 at the height of the 
propaganda battle over the deployment of us nuclear missiles in 
britain heseltine donned a flak jacket for a confrontation with 
antinuclear protesters at a missile base 
politically hes dead center in the party while mrs thatcher 
stands well to the right but many on the tory left distrust him 
for views that include enthusiasm for a program in the united 
states that requires unemployed to work for welfare 
he calls his political philosophy caring capitalism that 
contrasts with the freemarket stance of thatcherism 
for any democratic government the challenge is to take people 
a little further than they can go by themselves he once wrote 
and when need be to show that compassion for which the 
marketplace makes no allowance 
michael jones political editor of londons conservative sunday 
times wrote of heseltine he has the trick of making tory 
supporters feel good about themselves of making them feel that 
capitalism can have a moral base 
while a member of mrs thatchers government heseltine was the 
golden boy and seemed destined for bigger things 
the rift came in 1986 in a dispute over the buyout of the 
financially troubled british helicopter manufacturer westland plc 
heseltine always proeurope favored a european consortium while 
mrs thatcher favored the us corporation sikorsky 
to the surprise of nearly everyone heseltine stood up in the 
middle of a cabinet meeting in january 1986 and walked out 
of course i miss it hugely he mused earlier this year of 
his long exile from government i regretted profoundly the need 
to leave the cabinet but i have never had any doubts that it was 
the right thing to do 
most other casualties of the thatcher cabinets have fallen into 
political obscurity 
but heseltine conducted a patient campaign of a leader in 
waiting he has swept around the country addressing party meetings 
an average of five a week opening fetes spreading goodwill and 
glamour and assiduously avoiding direct criticism of mrs thatcher 
subtle criticisms however were always there particularly 
about her combative stance against the european community and a 
controversial new local government tax the socalled poll tax 
michael ray dibdin heseltine was born march 21 1933 into a 
middleclass welsh family his father was a structural engineer and 
parttime army colonel 
as an undergraduate at oxford heseltine mapped out his 
ambitions to make a fortune in business and become prime minister 
starting with a 1000pound legacy from his grandfather he made 
one fortune in property and then another in magazine publishing 
he and his wife anne who have two daughters and a son live in 
considerable style a magnificent period house in londons 
belgravia district and a country mansion where he has planted 2500 
species of trees and shrubs it also has a lake for his lifelong 
hobby of birdwatching 
i havent been driven by money heseltine once said i saw 
money as an important part of the process of being independent 
and in enabling me to pursue a political career 
after two unsuccessful attempts he was elected to parliament in 
1966 he got his first government job as minister of aerospace in 
1972 in edward heaths conservative government 
mrs thatcher appointed him to her first cabinet as environment 
secretary when she won power in 1979 and then defense secretary 
</TEXT>
