<TEXT>
minute injections of a highly poisonous 
toxin have been found effective and safe in treating a varity of 
involuntary muscle spasms a committee of experts announced today 
at the national institutes of health 
the toxin obtained from a bacteria that causes botulism food 
poisoning has been used successfully to treat spasms of the 
eyelids throat face and the vocal cords the panel said 
this is the most powerful toxin known said dr roger 
duvoisin of the robert wood medical school in new brunswick nj 
the complex protein known formally as botulinum toxin is 
produced by a bacteria in spoiled food and can lead to lethal food 
poisoning in large doses 
duvoisin said however that in very small injected doses the 
toxin has the ability to block signals from nerves to muscles this 
action will halt involuntary muscle spasms 
it has given relief where little was available before for 
muscle spasms duvoisin said 
the injections have been used for patients whose lives were 
blighted by such ailments as the involuntary and uncontrollable 
closing of the eyelids the inability to speak because of vocal 
cord spasms and facial tics that cause the muscles to contort 
repeatedly 
the committee organized by nih consisted of experts from around 
the country who evaluate clinical results from experimental use of 
the toxin in a variety of patients 
we have seen at this conference impressive evidence that this 
is the first choice of treatment for several disabling disorders 
duvoisin said 
because of the high success rates of the toxin treatment 
thousands of more patients have the potential to lead improved 
lives he said 
the committee called for additional studies to determine how 
else the toxin might be used and to better understand its precise 
action in the body 
injections of the toxin which can cost from 400 to 1800 
must usually be repeated three to four times a year for continuous 
symptomatic relief 
duvoisin emphasized that the injections only control the 
symptoms of the muscle spasms and are not a permanent cure 
</TEXT>
