<TEXT>
malcolm muggeridge once britains bestknown 
media celebrity died wednesday at a nursing home in southern 
england three months after suffering a stroke his family said he 
was 87 
muggeridge was an agnostic who became a roman catholic when he 
was nearly 80 and a youthful socialist who later mocked the trendy 
left he had one unchanging fascination death 
i rejoice in it i love it if it werent for death life 
would be unbearable muggeridge said in a television appearance 
seven years ago without a trace of morbidness 
muggeridge delivered the remark with the same puckish smile and 
twinkling eyes that enlivened his rigid views against 
contraception abortion divorce and pornography 
some commentators dubbed him st mugg while others said he 
railed in old age against vices such as smoking drinking and 
adultery that he had enjoyed as a younger man 
but for one who spent a long life talking writing pronouncing 
denouncing laughing at himself and others and infuriating many in 
the process he earned a rare reward few ever accused him of being 
a bore or a hypocrite 
journalist author teacher world war ii spy for britains mi6 
counterintelligence service editor and traveler muggeridge became 
famous through television in the 1950s and 60s 
his caustic commentaries waspish views on postimperial britain 
and a 1957 british broadcasting corp ban for what was perceived as 
an attack on the royal family made him familiar to millions 
he continued writing and interviewing after he moved in the 
1960s to the sussex village of robertsbridge where he lived with 
his wife kitty whom he married in 1927 he died in a sussex 
nursing home wednesday 
they had three surviving children one son died and nine 
grandchildren 
in middle life muggeridge a heavy smoker and drinker who 
once said i just liked getting drunk gave up both vices 
because the old must choose between sainthood and suicide 
muggeridge a selfconfessed unfaithful husband later changes 
his ways 
being unfaithful is the most despicable thing i have done in 
my life he said but i always owned up in the end and kitty 
understands 
through a career that included spells as a foreign correspondent 
in moscow and washington muggeridge remained both fascinated and 
repelled by politicians he espoused no political cause but loathed 
communism 
that was due party to his experiences during a 193233 
assignment in the soviet union as correspondent for britains 
liberal guardian newspaper 
muggeridges religious odyssey was tormented but conclusive 
he described that journey in his 1969 book jesus 
rediscovered which he wrote after he decided to become a 
committed christian and a nominal member of the church of england 
christianity to me is like a hopeless love affair he 
lamented in 1958 it is infinitely dear and infinitely 
unattainable 
he described his conversion to catholicism at age 80 as a 
homecoming picking up the lost threads of life he had found he 
couldnt take the anglican church seriously 
thomas malcolm muggeridge was born into a lower middleclass 
family and reared in south london his father henry a clerk in a 
shirtmaking firm was a lifelong socialist and for two years a 
labor party member of parliament 
after attending state schools muggeridge went to cambridge 
university and soon dropped his fathers socialist views 
he was mainly a freelance journalist but also held highpowered 
staff jobs such as the deputy editorship of britains conservative 
daily telegraph and editorship of the satirical magazine punch 
life holds no more wretched occupation than trying to make the 
english laugh was his verdict on punch 
the best thing about being a journalist he once said was the 
opportunity for contact with the eminent without being under the 
necessity to admire them or take them seriously 
winston churchill was a disaster he failed to notice the 
british empire was over and john f kennedy was a fraud but 
ronald reagan was not such a fool as people say 
he saw western civilization as doomed the inevitability of 
death as the most interesting aspect of life and life itself as an 
adventure mystery and for anyone of any sensitivity a 
disappointment 
human life i have come to feel in all its public or 
collective manifestations is only theater and mostly cheap 
melodrama at that he concluded 
there is nothing serious under the sun except love of 
fellowmortals and of god 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

