<TEXT>
germany and poland signed a treaty 
wednesday under which germany permanently surrendered its claim to 
40000 square miles of territory lost in world war ii about 
onethird of presentday poland 
the pact signed by foreign ministers hansdietrich genscher for 
germany and krzysztof skubiszewski for poland ended one of the 
most intractable diplomatic disputes of the postwar era 
although the treaty has long been one of polands chief foreign 
policy goals polish prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki avoided 
conveying any sense of triumph at the signing ceremony 
he instead stressed sympathy for the tragedy of millions of 
germans roughly expelled from their former homeland at the end of 
the war 
by recognizing the border on the oder and neisse rivers germany 
gives up any claims to historically german lands in pomerania 
silesia and east prussia now populated mainly by poles 
the victorious allies turned over the land to poland in 1945 to 
make up for an even greater expanse of polish territory taken in 
the east by the soviet union 
as a price for international consent to reunification this year 
germany agreed to make the border permanent 
the decision we have made is not an easy one for us 
germans for any of us including myself genscher said after 
signing the treaty and for those who have lost their home lands 
who suffered expulsion it is an especially painful one 
the 2page treaty called for building a peaceful european 
order in which borders will not divide 
the germans are not forwarding any territorial demands and 
will not forward any in the future genscher said 
because the frontier is now safe poles and germans can put 
aside mistrust and meet on a new footing he said he 
repeated a promise to lift the visa requirement for visiting poles 
by years end 
i am glad we have this stage behind us said solidarity 
leader lech walesa the frontrunning candidate in this months 
presidential election who met with genscher lets lift visas 
and other obstacles and there will be no problems 
mazowiecki took pains to address german concerns in what 
appeared to be the strongest apology ever made by a polish 
statesman to those who lost their homes 
the suffering of the german nation must be spoken about he 
said every harm remains a harm every tragedy remains a tragedy 
irrespective of the harms and tragedies that we ourselves 
experienced 
johann kroll a leader of the polish german minority present at 
the signing said the treaty does not create too much joy for 
us 
however it is necessary he said the present borders 
we consider to be temporary because we count on the fact that 
borders will vanish in the common europe 
