<TEXT>
the government said wednesday it is lifting 
controls on the prices of luxury goods in an effort to encourage 
production only hours later russias parliament declared the 
decree void in the largest of the 15 soviet republics 
the move by the russian federation set up the latest struggle in 
the war between the central soviet and russian governments it 
demonstrated the fragmentation and confusion plaguing the soviet 
union as the base of power moves from the kremlin to the republics 
the battle began with a decree by the national council of 
ministers that prices would be freed on goods of no essential 
influence on peoples living standards such as jewelry 
furniture and american cigarettes 
it marked the first time in decades that the government has 
completely freed an entire range of retail prices to respond to the 
market forces of supply and demand 
floating prices is an important element in the governments 
outline for converting the soviet union from a centrally planned 
economy in which the government sets all prices often regardless 
of the cost of production to a free market economy 
the councils decree applied to some of the items most in 
demand their prices have been fixed but in fact many of the goods 
are sold above the official price by corrupt store employees who 
sell them truckers who deliver them and factory workers who make 
them 
shoppers have to wait as long as 10 years to receive furniture 
at the official price but can get it immediately if they are 
willing to pay three times that rate 
other goods covered by the decree which was released by the 
tass news agency are natural furs carpets hightech 
electronics cut glassware china spare car parts and imports such 
as whiskey gin and american cigarettes certain meat products and 
fish delicacies are also included 
to prevent panic buying like that which preceded a round of 
price hikes planned for july 1 and later canceled the 
government announced the action just one day before it was to take 
effect on thursday 
the government said freeing prices would provide extra 
incentives to increase the production of consumer goods and 
saturate the market it also said the measure would undermine the 
black market for the items 
the decree drew immediate criticism 
i consider it pointless radical legislator gennady filshin 
told the russian federations parliament an account of his remarks 
by the independent news agency interfax did not report his reasons 
for opposing the move 
the russian council of ministers in its retaliation said the 
national decree has no force on russian territory and forbade sale 
of the affected goods until further notice it said wine vodka and 
tobacco goods would continue to be sold at current statefixed 
prices 
it ordered an inventory of the affected goods to be conducted 
for the purpose of preserving them and said local government 
leaders would be held personally responsible for the results 
even a member of the national council of ministers which 
adopted the decree criticized it 
deputy prime minister stepan sitaryan said there would be many 
bruises he predicted that prices of the goods affected would 
double and that there would be a chain reaction that would drive 
up the prices of other goods he said some businesses might 
intentionally decrease production to drive up prices artificially 
so they can get a higher profit 
many of these problems he said could have been avoided if 
prices were freed simultaneously with a move to privatize 
businesses and end the state monopoly of the economy 
as the old central planning system collapses hidden inflation 
and hoarding have exacerbated many perennial shortages and created 
new ones 
soviets have been hoarding anything with lasting value 
including many of the goods whose prices are being raised in the 
decree 
many people are particularly worried about the coming winter a 
public opinion poll published in an edition of the weekly moscow 
news released wednesday said 62 percent of those questioned fear 
hunger in the next few months twentysix percent had no fear and 
12 percent did not know 
the poll conducted by the allunion center of study of public 
opinion did not give a margin of error 
an accompanying open letter by a group of prominent politicians 
and economists said the government should head off difficulties 
this winter by opening strategic reserves saved in the event of 
war 
the country is slipping into an abyss a civil war they 
warned unless a number of urgent decisive measures are taken a 
tragedy will be inevitable 
