<DOCNO> AP901114-0099 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
cigarettes increase smokers pain tolerance and 
could therefore block the chest pains that serve as a warning for 
heart disease researchers said wednesday 
in studies with 20 male smokers ages 19 to 44 the researchers 
found that the tolerance to pain increased with each of three 
cigarettes smoked 
the study presented at the annual meeting of the amerian heart 
association was conducted by asking the smokers to keep away from 
cigarettes for 12 hours and then smoke three cigarettes at timed 
intervals a hot probe was touched to their arms after each 
cigarette and warmed until it reached the threshhold temperature 
that produced pain said dr paula miller of the university of 
north carolina school of medicine the principal author of the 
study 
a statistically significant rise in the temperatures the men 
could tolerate occurred after they smoked the cigarettes she said 
we have a lot of confidence in our findings because the 
responses were so consistent said the senior author of the 
study dr david sheps also of the university of north carolina 
almost every man showed increases in threshhold and tolerance 
temperatures immediately after smoking a cigarette he said 
smokers are known to have a higher prevalence of what is called 
silent ischemia said miller 
silent ischemia occurs when blood flow to the heart is briefly 
interrupted because of the buildup of fatty deposits and 
cholesterol in the arteries that nourish the heart 
in many people ischemia produces the chest pain known as 
angina which is an indicator of heart disease in silent ischemia 
however there is no pain to call attention to the underlying heart 
disease 
miller has been trying to understand why silent ischemia occurs 
and she said that the painmasking effects of smoking might explain 
why it is more common in smokers 
in another study she showed that the naturally occuring 
painrelieving substances called endorphins also may help mask the 
pain associated with ischemia 
people whose bodies naturally produce more endorphins may be 
more likely to suffer from silent ischemia she said 
the american heart association estimates that 2 million 
americans suffer from angina as many as 3 million or 4 million 
americans may suffer from silent ischemia the heart association 
estimates 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

