<DOCNO> AP901114-0117 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
botulinum toxin bestknown as a cause of 
lethal food poisoning has been found to be safe and effective in 
small injections for a variety of muscle spasms a national 
institutes of health committee announced wednesday 
the toxin obtained from bacteria that cause botulism food 
poisoning has been used successfully to treat involuntary 
clinching of muscles in the eyelids throat face and the vocal 
cords the panel said 
it also shows promise in the treatment of stuttering 
misalignment of the eyes and for cramps experienced by musicians 
writers and typists 
dr roger duvoisin chairman of the nih panel and on the faculty 
of the robert wood medical school in new brunswick nj said the 
toxin is an example of a highly lethal poison that can be 
beneficial used in small doses 
this is the most powerful toxin known said duvoisin and 
yet he noted it has given relief where little was available 
before 
he said there are hundreds of thousands of americans who suffer 
from some form of muscle spasm that can be treated by the toxin 
known formally as botulinum toxin the substance is a complex 
protein produced by bacteria that in contaminated food can lead to 
lethal poisoning 
but very small doses injected directly into specific muscles 
duvoisin said have the ability to block signals from nerves to 
muscles this action will halt involuntary muscle spasms 
muscle spasms can be quiet disabling maladies said 
duvoisin 
spasms can distort facial expressions or cause eyelids to close 
tightly so that victims have to pry them open by hand or cause the 
voice to jam when the vocal cords are involved unbalanced muscles 
can cause eyes to be crossed or pointed fixedly to the side 
duvoisin said that a form of muscle spasm cut short the piano 
career of robert schuman and led to a cramping disorder now 
described as the schuman hand writers and typist have similar 
problems 
the nih panel which evaluated the use of the toxin said all of 
these conditions may be helped by small injections of the poison 
mrs robert bruce the president of the benign essential 
blepharospasm research foundation and a member of the panel said 
that the toxin shots were able to restore her to a full life 
her problem started she said when muscles controlling both 
eyelids suddenly contracted and refused to open 
mrs bruce said she was unable to see unless she pried her 
eyelids open by hand when the lids were released they jammed 
closed once more 
i couldnt work i couldnt drive i couldnt cook said 
mrs bruce i couldnt even go shopping someone had to lead me 
around by the hand 
she tried a number of treatments including hypnotism 
biofeedback and 12 types of medications but nothing worked 
then a doctor injected specific muscles in her face with small 
doses of the botulinum toxin 
the effect was to loosen and weaken the malfunctioning muscles 
and mrs bruce said it enables her to control her eyelids normally 
duvoisin said the toxin injections work for only a few months 
and then the effect wears off he said there is no apparent limit 
on the number new injection rounds that can be used without side 
effects 
the therapy takes a high degree of expertise and only a limited 
number of experts are skilled in its use he said more are being 
trained now 
a round of treatment with the toxin can cost from 400 to 
1800 duvoisin said 
</TEXT>
