many british prime ministers serve long and 
glorious terms in office but for some the end has been sudden and 
sorrowful 
few go out voluntarily in the style of lord salisbury who 
retired in 1902 after 13 years in office 
and since then no one has served longer than margaret thatcher 
who faces her first serious challenge after 11 years in power 
she has lasted longer than sir winston churchill and herbert 
asquith who each served eight years eight months both resigned 
under pressure from colleagues 
churchill lost the first peacetime election in 1945 but when a 
labor party government fell in 1951 churchill was back at 10 
downing street the prime ministers home 
everyone has his day and some days last longer than others 
he said in a speech to the house of commons in 1952 
churchills days of power lasted until 1955 when at age 80 he 
resigned under pressure from party colleagues who saw he could no 
longer concentrate on cabinet business 
his successor sir anthony eden lasted only two years his 
health and then his career broken by the suez crisis 
churchill lived a decade after retiring but others died soon 
after relinquishing power 
the liberal sir henry campbellbannerman was dead 17 days after 
resigning in 1908 the conservative bonar law lived only five 
months after he quit in 1923 
neville chamberlain who was replaced by churchill in the early 
months of world war ii lived only another six months 
asquith was maneuvered out in 1916 in the midst of a world war 
by liberal party colleagues headed by david lloyd george who 
believed they could conduct the war more effectively 
