<TEXT>
after four years of contentious debate among 
environmentalists homeowners and rival energy suppliers federal 
regulators wednesday approved construction of a 583 million 
pipeline to bring natural gas from canada to the northeast 
in the end tight energy supplies in new england new york and 
new jersey outweighed the concerns of opponents of the iroquois 
pipeline who ranged from wildcat oil drillers in the southwest to 
pop psychologist dr joyce brothers whose hudson valley estate in 
new york would be crossed by the line 
jerry langdon a member of the federal energy regulatory 
commission said wednesdays unanimous decision by his agency 
represented a move to make greater use of north american if not 
just us energy supplies 
robert j reid president of the iroquois gas transmission 
system a consortium of us and canadian gas companies and 
utilities based in shelton conn said it was imperative that 
we receive ferc approval in november to maintain our timetable for 
constructing the pipeline 
the pipeline will extend 370 miles from the st lawrence river 
through the woodlands of upstate new york beneath the hudson 
river into affluent sections of western connecticut and across 
long island sound to long island iroquois officials hope to have 
gas flowing to new york and new england by november 1991 and to 
complete the line by january 1992 
iroquois still has a few regulatory hurdles to clear including 
permits from the us army corps of engineers for waterway 
crossings and import permits from the energy department expected 
to be pro forma under the uscanada free trade agreement 
thousands of property owners along the route have not yet agreed to 
let iroquois pay to cross their land and iroquois may have to 
settle some of those cases in court 
this has been controversial almost since it was filed in 
1986 said susan court associate general counsel of the 
commission for gas and oil 
iroquois is designed to deliver 575 million cubic feet of gas 
daily or enough to meet the energy needs of 15 million homes 
though one reason it is being built is to make gas available for 
electricity generation 
the daily amount could supply between three and four large 
electric power plants if it were all devoted to that use though 
utilities receiving the gas may use it for any of their customers 
the gas supplied by iroquois will increase the energy supply 
flowing to the northeast by 5 percent according to reid iroquois 
could double transmission capacity with additional compressors 
existing gas pipelines to the northeast from us gas fields 
have been running at capacity for years no one sought to build new 
ones 
transcanada pipelines ltd one of iroquois several owners 
estimated the new line will generate 1 billion per year in exports 
for canada canada has been supplying natural gas to the united 
states since the 1960s but mostly in the west and midwest 
domestic energy suppliers complained that iroquois will 
discourage production and will compete unfairly with us pipelines 
and oil companies 
iroquois gas however will be more expensive than us gas and 
cheaper than oil according to a formula approved by the commission 
that ties the price to those two commodities 
we really view oil as the competition not other natural 
gas said iroquois spokesman gary davis 
