<TEXT>
some members of a scientific panel said 
wednesday they should have moved faster to draft guidelines for 
adding steroids to the treatment of a killer pneumonia in people 
with aids 
in retrospect it should have happened more quickly said 
paul meier professor of statistics at the university of chicago 
and vice chairman of the panel that convened last may 
aids activists also said the panel took too long but federal 
medical officials said these critics were disregarding some 
important facts 
still other panel members said the approval process could not 
have been significantly speeded up 
the national institute of allergy and infectious diseases on 
oct 10 sent an alert to physicians informing them that recent 
studies had found benefits among some patients with pneumocycstis 
carinii pneumonia whose treatment was supplemented with steroids 
steorids are known to weaken the immune system and aids is a 
disease of a collapsing immune system 
the letter sent to 2600 medical practitioners was based on 
the findings of the 17member panel organized by the institute and 
the university of california at san diego 
mike merdian executive director of the national association of 
people with aids said the five months it took the panel to come up 
with its recommendations was unconscionable and unethical 
but not unusual 
weve long said there are many therapies available were not 
aware of he said 
but the chairman of the panel rejected the criticism and said 
the time it took members to analyze the studies was well spent 
trying to agree on the wording of any recommendations as to which 
patients would benefit most from steroid treatment in what doses 
and for what period of time 
the five months was a relatively short period said dr 
henry masur panel chairman and chief of critical care the national 
institutes of health clinical center i dont think it will ever 
get much faster 
since steroids weaken the immune system the whole concept of 
giving steroids to someone with aids is very novel and 
controversial masur said 
among the concerns are that steroids can increase the rate at 
which the aids virus replicates and make it more likely other 
infectious complications develop he said 
it was vitally important to make sure that steroids 
unequivocally improved survival and it was important to prove that 
while improving from one disease it didnt cause numerous other 
potentially fatal problems he said 
pneumocystis carinii pneumonia is the biggest killer of people 
with aids about 40000 cases are expected to occur this year in 
the united states 
the broad outlines of a consensus on the steroid issue was 
reached may 15 but it wasnt until the end of august that the 
experts agreed on the technical details such as for whom the 
therapy should be recommended for and in what doses 
they decided that the studies showed that patients who benefit 
most from steroids along with standard therapy were those who had 
moderate or severe pneumocystis but that there was no evidence of 
benefit for patients with mild disease 
bernard bihari executivemedical director of the community 
research initiative which treats aids patients in new york said 
the issue was too important for lengthy disagreements to stall the 
discussions 
they should have locked them in a room and said youre not 
coming out until you have a statement he said 
dr samuel bozzette assistant professor of medicine at the 
university of california at san diego and a panel member said that 
in a perfect system it could have been shorter but it was not 
an unreasonable amount of time 
he added that when you release one of these consensus 
statements you are setting a worldwide standard of care and one 
has to make sure that the recommendations are as carefully 
considered as possible 
but he also agreed with meier that the documents could have been 
passed around more quickly and daytoday processes could have 
moved quicker 
meier said that the panel which took about three months to 
complete its part of the task ould have achieved that goal in 
about one month but nobody set a deadline 
a failure to recognize it the process was dragging is where 
i would fault us meier said 
