the soviet government announced a shakeup of the 
state television monopoly wednesday creating four separate 
companies in a move intended to increase competition and improve 
quality 
leonid p kravchenko 52 was named as the new head of the state 
committee for television and radio known in russian as 
gosteleradio he has been the directorgeneral of the official tass 
news agency since 1988 
he replaces mikhail nenashev who will become chairman of the 
soviet committee on the press nanashev is under orders to propose 
fundamental reforms in the structure of the print media 
both personnel changes were made by decree of president mikhail 
s gorbachev kravchenkos successor as head of tass has not been 
named 
the government newspaper izvestia reported that instead of one 
central television station with four channels gosteleradio has 
decided to make each channel an independent company with full 
creative and commercial independence 
the first company channel one will continue to carry the 
countrys principal news programs and remain an outlet for 
government information and cultural programming its directors will 
be gorbachev the supreme soviet legislature and the national 
government 
the second company to be called commonwealth will be 
devoted to programming from studios in the 15 soviet republics 
a new moscow tv company a jointstock enterprise will run the 
third channel the original stockholders will be gosteleradio the 
moscow city council the moscow regional council and various public 
organizations 
the fourth company called 21st century tv will take the 
current educational channel as its base gosteleradio said writers 
and artists unions and other public organizations have been 
invited to become its founders 
leningrad tv the only channel that has been independent of 
central television also is being invited to form a joint stock 
company izvestia said 
gosteleradio said the changes would democratize the artistic 
process strengthen the spirit of competition and as a result 
raise the quality of broadcasting 
gosteleradio itself will be among the founders of all four new 
companies because it controls virtually all the equipment and 
existing broadcast revenues izvestia said 
in a presidential decree carried wednesday by tass gorbachev 
gave nenashev two weeks to submit proposals for reforming the 
committee on the press 
the decree says a major reorganization of the press is needed to 
ensure citizens rights to receive and disseminate information 
broader rights for publishing houses and printing enterprises and 
delineation of the functions of central and localauthorities 
earlier this year the supreme soviet passed a new law on 
freedom of the press giving legal backbone to gorbachevs policy 
of glasnost or greater openness 
in the past year several leading soviet publications including 
the weekly newspaper moscow news and the magazine ogonyok have 
gained formal independence from ownership by government and 
communist organizations but most newspapers and magazines still 
belong to political bodies or state organizations 
the reorganization of the press could pave the way for more 
independent publications and privately owned profitmaking 
publishing houses 
