<TEXT>
a former elementary school teacher accused 
of molesting dozens of his male students over 30 years some of 
them sons of formerly abused boys was sentenced wednesday to 20 
years in prison 
douglas marks 63 also was fined 25000 
marks had no visible reaction when the sentence was announced by 
state district judge frank davis and he was led from the courtroom 
in handcuffs about 40 people showed up at the sentencing 
including marks brother bob former speaker of the montana house 
marks pleaded guilty july 9 to four counts of felony sexual 
assault for molesting four of his elementary school students 
between 1985 and 1989 the fathers of two of those boys said they 
too had been victims of marks years ago 
prosecutors said marks molested many other male students during 
his lengthy teaching career in boulder and nearby clancy 
court records cited 22 instances of molestation dating to 1956 
most too old to prosecute jefferson county attorney richard 
llewellyn says he has found 45 victims 
paul myrhow whose complaint against marks led to the 
investigation that resulted in the charges and who took his 
complaints public was in the courtroom 
it was more than i expected he said i thought he was 
going to get away with no prison time 
davis sentenced marks to a 40year term but suspended 20 years 
davis also said if marks is paroled he can have no contact with 
anyone younger than 18 years old 
at a hearing last week davis refused to allow some of marks 
victims to testify saying i wasnt going to embarrass this poor 
man any more 
marks should be eligible for parole in about five years 
llewellyn said davis said marks could not be paroled until he paid 
the 25000 fine which would be used to pay for counseling of his 
victims and other youths involved in sex crimes 
marks is a member of a prominent local family that owns 
substantial ranch property in the helenaboulder area and a sawmill 
in clancy 
llewellyn said he was satisfied with the sentence adding that 
marks had shown little remorse for the victims 
defense lawyer richard gillespie had asked that marks be 
sentenced to a treatment program and 238 days in jail most of 
which would have been served on weekends 
llewellyn took issue with suggestions by some that investigators 
acted too slowly in bringing marks to justice he said the state 
acted as quickly as it could interviewing dozens of witnesses in 
several states 
marks had built a reputation as a devoted and selfless teacher 
in boulder but questions about his morals were raised as early as 
1959 
he was forced to resign from jefferson county high school that 
year after three boys said he molested them but he later taught at 
nearby clancy and then returned to boulder in 1965 as an elementary 
school teacher 
in a related development tuesday boulder school officials said 
an independent investigation had shown that five people had 
reported improper conduct by marks to school officials 
the school board hired two investigators in september to look 
into allegations that school officals were slow to act on 
complaints about marks the investigators reported their findings 
to a board committee at a closed meeting monday 
superintendent of schools richard moe said the boards conduct 
committee is reviewing information and giving anyone who allegedly 
acted improperly a chance to respond he would not elaborate 
