<TEXT>
the prime minister of luxembourg told 
parliament wednesday that nato organized a network of clandestine 
resistance fighters at the start of the cold war 
nato was the initiator and the coordinator but each member 
nation was master of its own operation prime minister jacque 
santer said adding that virtually all the european nations in nato 
took part he said the network was recently disbanded in 
luxembourg 
nato officials have refused to comment on the alliances role in 
the network of guerrilla groups organized as part of preparations 
for a possible soviet attack 
nato does not comment on matters of security said a 
spokesman at nato headquarters 
former nato secretary general joseph luns said he had never 
heard of the guerrilla network but acknowledged it could have 
operated behind his back 
the government of luxembourg said it participated in an allied 
network of guerrilla operatives 
the very principle of such a concept of patriotic resistance 
cannot be disputed in the strategic context at that time the 
government said referring to the start of the cold war 
the guerrilla network was brought to light last month in italy 
where it takes its name operation gladio from the swords used 
by roman gladiators in italy gladio is under investigation for 
possible links to rightwing terrorism a similar inquiry is under 
way in belgium 
the existence of the resistance networks has been disclosed in 
italy germany france belgium the netherlands denmark norway 
austria spain greece and portugal the guerrilla groups became 
public knowledge years ago in norway and turkey but debate in 
those countries drew little notice elsewhere 
on wednesday guy coeme belgiums defense minister 
acknowledged the existence of a belgian network codenamed stay 
behind 
he said it was in touch with similar groups in other nato 
nations through a coordination committee that most recently met in 
brussels in october but coeme said he could not say now what 
links the belgian network had with nato 
in bonn the german government confirmed plans for covert 
anticommunist actions in case of war but denied any military unit 
took part 
reports that link the precautions mentioned with expressions 
like commando group or guerrilla army are false government 
spokesman hans klein said without elaboration 
the german newspaper die welt reported wednesday that us 
intelligence agents recruited hundreds of guerrillas and laid 
weapons caches across western europe at the start of the cold war 
jean gol a former belgian justice minister was quoted 
wednesday as saying the government knew of a secret anticommunist 
network in belgium 
shortly after i became minister of justice on jan 16 1984 
i was informed about the belgian network gol told the daily 
newspaper le peuple he said belgiums 1984 budget contained 
328000 to modernize the networks communication equipment 
in turkey the independent daily milliyet said a unit known as 
the special war department within the general staff was most likely 
the turkish branch of operation gladio 
it quoted former premier bulent ecevit as saying the unit had 
been funded by the united states until 1974 after that he said 
the unit sought funds from the defense budget 
patriotic volunteers were members of the group they were 
trained specially to launch a counter guerrilla operation in the 
event that the country was occupied ecevit was quoted as saying 
existence of the turkish group was well known and often became 
the focus of debate in political circles and newspapers during a 
wave of terrorism in 1970s leftist groups questioned the possible 
role of the organization in rightwing terrorism 
british intelligence expert nigel west said wednesday that us 
and british agents were heavily involved in creating european 
resistance networks 
in a telephone interview in london west editor of intelligence 
quarterly magazine said such networks were often continuations of 
plans first created in world war ii 
initially they arose out of allied desire not to repeat wartime 
mistakes when german advances caught allies without plans for 
staybehind fighters said west pen name of conservative 
lawmaker rupert allason author of books on britains mi5 and mi6 
security services 
he said such operations in britain were disbanded because a 
soviet invasion of britain has never been regarded as a tactical 
practicality 
but he added that curiously enough they still find caches of 
arms in funny places 
