<TEXT>
the fate of americas invisible hostages is 
bound up in a maze of shifting interests and allegiances 
crosscurrents that could yet serve the cause of freedom for six 
us captives in lebanon 
pressure and attention are concentrated on the confrontation 
with iraq and on nearly 1000 americans detained deployed as 
human shield hostages at potential military targets or hiding from 
saddam husseins regime there are no clear and current demands for 
specific concessions as the price of release for the 13 western 
hostages in lebanon 
but there have been frequent reports that one step might lead to 
another 
and in those circumstances a gesture need not be a surrender to 
the demands of kidnappers a policy that bars negotiating 
concessions to terrorists does not necessarily preclude granting 
what is not demanded 
israel is in a position to take steps of that sort that 
government controls the forces holding an estimated 340 shiite 
captives in southern lebanon forty others were freed on oct 1 
the israelis also hold a militant moslem cleric captured last year 
sheik abdul karim obeid 
freeing such prisoners would not necessarily get the western 
hostages out of captivity but even a gesture toward that end might 
take a little of the strain out of usisraeli relations under 
stress since the persian gulf crisis began and worsened by the 
killings of 19 palestinian arabs in rioting at temple mount in 
jerusalem on oct 8 israel has refused to accept a united nations 
investigation of the shootings an inquiry supported by the united 
states which also voted for a un resolution denouncing the 
shootings 
that episode posed a problem for the fragile us alliance with 
arab states in opposition to the iraqi occupation of kuwait and 
the israelis suspect washington of tilting away from them in favor 
of the unsanctioned front against saddam 
the original ransom demand for at least some of the american 
hostages has ironically been met or rendered moot by the aug 2 
iraqi invasion of kuwait it was a demand for the release of 15 
shiite moslems imprisoned in kuwait since 1983 for terrorist 
bombings at the us and french embassies government buildings and 
oil facilities that price tag for the freedom of western hostages 
had been repeated periodically in messages from islamic holy war 
the group holding two us hostages 
its captives are terry anderson chief middle east correspondent 
of the associated press now in his sixth year as a hostage and 
thomas sutherland a dean at the american university in beirut 
kidnapped later in 1985 the western hostages in lebanon all are 
believed held by factions linked with a proiranian group called 
hezbollah or party of god 
the kuwaiti prisoners are out now the two lebanese shiites 
among them said to be back in lebanon the others most of them 
iraqis who had opposed saddam hussein are believed to be in iran 
although middle east analysts say there is no firm information on 
their whereabouts nor is it known whether they escaped or were 
freed or were sezed by the iraqis in the invasion and later 
turned over to iran as part of saddams effort to improve relations 
with his old enemy 
in opposing saddam hussein the united states is aligned with 
syria another power in the hostage situation a move to free 
hostages could help make that alliance of necessity into a more 
durable relationship the syrians hope eventually to gain us 
support for a general middle east peace conference a forum in 
which they would seek to reclaim territory lost to israel 
secretary of state james a baker iii met with syrian president 
hafez assad in damascus on sept 14 and said he raised the hostage 
question then he said assad did not indicate any expectation 
that they would be released soon 
a month later the syrians used the military forces with which 
they dominate much of lebanon to put down the rebellion of a 
christian faction in beirut backing the government in imposing a 
settlement under which rival militias are to withdraw from the 
capital ending a long civil war there are about 40000 syrian 
troops in lebanon 
hezbollah has moved its militia from southern beirut to villages 
in eastern and southeastern lebanon syrian forces controlled the 
roads from beirut and in moving eastward the captors would have 
had to take their hostages across those lines 
syrian officials have said repeatedly that they want to help 
gain release of the hostages to end a situation they say they do 
not control 
iran is said to wield a more powerful influence although it 
too is indirect the latest in a series of reports of imminent 
release for british hostages came this week from a radical iranian 
leader who said he opposed it 
more moderate iranian officials are said to favor release of the 
hostages this year as a step toward improved relations with the 
west as president bush said when he came to office good will 
begets good will 
 
editors note walter r mears vice president and columnist 
for the associated press has reported on washington and national 
politics for more than 25 years 
