<TEXT>
todays generation of selma blacks take integration for granted 
and view bloody sunday as something from long ago that they learn 
about during black history month like slavery 
and yet not unlike cities of all sizes in every region selma 
still feels the ache of what has become a national migraine reduced 
to a single syllable race 
black eligible voters in selma and dallas county now outnumber 
whites barely under smitherman selma has gerrymandered its wards 
so that four blacks and four whites sit on the city council the 
council president elected atlarge is currently white council 
members have an unwritten agreement that a person of the same race 
will be appointed to replace any one of them leaving office in 
midterm 
very often in selma seemingly neutral issues that come before 
the council are resolved along racial lines many chalk it up to 
the citys heritage of confrontation it seems to have left selma 
as fragile as a house of cards the whole town hoping nobody will 
bump the table 
somehow smitherman has managed to keep the balance to walk the 
tightrope as he says without losing control 
joe smitherman is a man of great cunning says the rev fred 
reese he knows how to manipulate the white people to accept 
changes that will benefit the black people and them too really 
he knows just how far to go and still keep white support without 
losing black support 
reese is the principal of selma high school back in 1964 he was 
the head of the dallas county voters league the person who lured 
martin luther king to selma for the voting rights crusade he was 
also one of the few blacks who managed to register to vote despite 
the obstacles of the time in the 1964 mayors race he voted for 
smitherman 
joe and i are the same age we grew up in the same part of 
town in similar circumstances said reese blacks can identify 
with him 
for the 30 years before smitherman ran there hadnt been a real 
race for mayor selmas ruling gentry passed the office from one of 
their number to the next like a fiefdom the only requirement was 
to keep things as is 
smitherman then was a brash upstart he was a gawky young 
appliance salesman with a long neck and big ears and no friends at 
the country club he managed to get elected to the city council 
where he became a royal pain he wanted to do city business in the 
open for example instead of the back room brash 
he ran for mayor pledging to represent all the people not the 
favored few and his campaign flyers underlined the word all 
i figured everybody had a favored few they didnt like he 
said i was right when i won the old guard wouldnt even give 
me a key to city hall i had to get one made 
the civil rights demonstrations behind him smitherman became 
the busiest man in town he pushed through a penny sales tax and 
did things people could see and touch paved and lighted streets 
new garbage trucks fire engines sewer lines 
he became an expert at wheedling money out of washington money 
the old guard shunned as tainted inviting federal 
interference 
only thing tainted about it smitherman told them is 
taint enough of it 
and more visible and touchable things appeared each new project 
overlapping the last new libraries new city hall new housing 
projects schools museums fountains trees and flowers and parks 
train crossings were a hazard he stopped a 180car freight with 
a police car and ticketed the conductor for blocking streets the 
railroad rescheduled 
he refused to pay the citys electric bill until the power 
company explained its passon charges so the people could know 
what they were paying for 
when ku klux klansmen showed up on the city hall steps he called 
them white trash and ran them out of town blacks applauded he 
padlocked the antipoverty office because only 5 percent of the 
paid employees were white not enough whites applauded 
at the 20th anniversary observance of bloody sunday smitherman 
went to the pulpit of brown chapel where martin luther king had 
preached and said my hands are as dirty as the others we were 
wrong im sorry he shared a hymnal with jesse jackson and sang 
we shall overcome 
i suppose ive been the most visible person in the state short 
of the governor smitherman said and a lot of people expected 
me to run for higher office 
when i was younger i gave some thought to it but after a few 
terms i discovered its hard for mayors to do that 
mayors cant duck issues or avoid taking sides for mayors 
the public is as close as the sidewalk you either get the garbage 
picked up or you dont you either remove the dangerous tree or you 
dont you cant tell an angry citizen that youll have a committee 
look into it not if you want to get reelected 
also you need what i call the big mules the money boys who 
finance your campaign and dont let you forget where you got the 
money ive shifted around so much politically backing democrats 
republicans whatever that the big mules who know me could never 
be sure if id stay hitched 
anyhow selma is all i really care about and being mayor of 
selma has been sufficient two more years and im history 
</TEXT>
