computer punchcard 
it will be as quaint as people who use calligraphy pens he 
quipped the keyboard will be considered an accessory in the 
future 
bricklin is so confident that handwriting recognition will be 
the way many computers take in information he started a software 
company to develop programs for the machines 
so far only a few rudimentary handwritingbased computers are on 
the market one sold by grid systems corp a subsidiary of tandy 
corp is a flat 4pound handheld device that resembles an 
etchasketch it recognizes numbers and capital block letters 
written with a special pen on its screen 
among sample uses for the grid machine shown at comdex are an 
entryorder system for food companies that supply supermarkets and 
an electronic accident report for police 
with the retail order form the user writes in the quantity of 
various products using the special pen the computer then 
reproduces the figures in its own typeface 
with the accident report the officer writes his name and the 
computer reproduces it the officer then depicts the accident scene 
by selecting from various road diagrams traffic signs and 
vehicles all represented by pictures that can be moved when the 
pen is touched to the computer screen the reoprt later can be 
printed on almost any computer porinter 
as computers become smaller the keyboard becomes impractical 
said robert carr of go corp which also is developing software 
for handwritingbased machines 
the keyboards dont shrink down very well he said you 
have to file your fingertips to a tiny point 
bricklin believes handwriting recognition will be combined with 
voice recognition to virtually replace keyboards 
he showed a videotape of two voice recognition systems already 
on the market one can be used by doctors to enter patient records 
into a computer it recognizes a limited vocabulary of medical 
terms the other device can draw certain objects on a macintosh 
computer screen by recognizing words for certain objects such as 
circle 
while neither is very sophisticated bricklin said they are a 
vast improvement over machines of a few years ago 
carr believes keyboardless computers will be more socially 
acceptable he said keyboardbased portable computers can seem 
intrusive while a penbased computer is similar to taking notes on 
a pad that will make them more practical when they are toted 
around to meetings or other social situations 
part of the advancement in personal computers will be enabled by 
vastly more powerful microprocessors the experts said by 1995 
the chips used in personal machines will exceed the power of 
todays roomsized mainframe computers they said 
</TEXT>
