media baron rupert murdochs news international 
said tuesday it is examining a merger proposal between one of its 
british newspapers called today and another london paper the 
sunday correspondent 
the company said in a statement it had been approached last 
weekend by the weekly sunday correspondent suggesting the merger 
with the daily today 
the proposal was to have a roundtheweek operation in which 
news international would have a minority share news international 
said 
the sunday correspondent was launched sept 17 1989 there are 
11 papers published in britain on sundays and they compete 
ferociously for readers 
in a bid to win greater popularity with a mass national 
readership the sunday correspondent abandoned its broadsheet 
format on sept 30 to become a tabloid 
this followed a fall in sales to below the 350000 copies needed 
to break even a financial rescue package and the resignation of 
editor peter cole in what it called the interests of the 
continued shareholder support 
the times of london another murdoch paper said the papers 
current circulation is below 300000 
sunday correspondent shareholders include the chicago tribune 
the british daily newspaper the guardian robert maxwell owner of 
mirror group newspapers whose british tabloid flagship is the daily 
mirror and saudi arabian investor wafiq saeed 
publisher eddie shah launched today in march 1986 as britains 
first electronically produced national daily paper it accelerated 
a technological revolution in britains national newspaper 
industry which until 1986 was dominated by outdated production 
methods largely as a result of union militancy 
but today did not thrive under shah and businessman tiny 
rowlands international conglomerate lonrho plc bought it from him 
later in 1986 
lonrho cut todays heavy financial losses and increased its 
advertising revenue and circulation but sold it to murdoch in 1987 
for 38 million pounds which was then worth about 608 million 
the paper now sells 588000 copies a day 
the times reported a merger would result in significant cost 
savings involving job losses at both newspapers 
news international said no deal had been reached and that it had 
issued the statement simply to avoid unnecessary and inaccurate 
rumors whilst this approach is being examined 
it said it was continuing efforts to make today profitable 
murdoch who was born in australia but has become a us 
citizen controls about a third of britains national daily and 
sunday newspaper circulation in addition to the times and today 
he owns the the sun and two sunday newspapers 
on nov 2 his fourchannel sky television service announced it 
would merge with its rival british satellite broadcastings five 
channels to form a new fivechannel network called british sky 
broadcasting 
