<DOCNO> AP901114-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the german government on wednesday 
announced plans to cut defense spending by 25 billion marks or 
17 billion next year and impose no new taxes in the first budget 
of united germany 
partial budget proposals approved by the conservative cabinet 
on wednesday and outlined by finance minister theo waigel also 
called for setting a federal deficit cap of 70 billion marks or 
47 billion for 1991 and reducing the federal deficit to 30 
billion marks or 20 billion by 1994 
the 1990 federal deficit was 668 billion marks or 45 billion 
a detailed budget is expected to be presented to the new unified 
german government next spring 
the partial proposal did not give an overall spending figure for 
the united country but waigel said he expected spending to be no 
more than 2 percent higher than the combined 1990 budgets of east 
and west germany 
officials said the two countries had total budgets of 396 
billion marks or about 265 billion before they unified on oct 
3 
waigel said he did not expect there would be tax increases 
if decisive measures are taken tax increases will not be 
necessary waigel said it would be counterproductive to take 
measures that weaken the german economy 
the two german governments spent about 57 billion marks or 38 
billion on defense in 1990 an official in the finance ministry 
said the 1991 cuts of 25 billion marks would represent a 4 
percent reduction in defense spending 
earlier in the week defense minister gerhard stoltenberg 
outlined plans to cut germanys armed forces to 370000 from about 
525000 over the next four years germany agreed to the troop 
reduction in exchange for the soviet unions blessing of united 
germanys continued nato membership and the gradual withdrawal of 
soviet troops from former east german territory 
waigel told reporters the government expected the economy to 
grow 3 percent to 35 percent in what used to be west germany in 
1991 he said projected growth for a united germany in 1991 would 
be 2 percent to 3 percent 
inflation was expected to run about 3 percent next year but 
could decline to 25 percent waigel added 
western states must show solidarity and bear more of the cost of 
german unity the minister added living and industrial standards 
in the five new eastern german states created after oct 3 
unification were devastated by 40 years of communist central 
planning and neglect 
the 1991 budget plans call for the federal government to spend 
74 billion marks or 50 billion and the western states an 
additional 3 billion marks or 2 billion on unification costs 
waigel said the federal and western state governments had spent 
46 billion marks or 31 billion on unification in 1990 
waigel said it was impossible to predict how the budget might be 
affected if war breaks out in the persian gulf 
germanys constitution prohibits it from sending soldiers to 
nonnato countries but chancellor helmut kohl and stoltenberg both 
favor changing the constitution to allow german troops to take part 
in un actions kohl says the new parliament to be elected dec 
2 will consider the matter 
</TEXT>
