<TEXT>
us agriculture secretary clayton yeutter 
said wednesday the united states would not budge on its demand for 
sharp cuts in agricultural subsidies in the current round of world 
trade talks 
at a joint news conference with yeutter us trade 
representative carla hills said agriculture was the key to 
resolving the uruguay round of the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade 
mrs hills said quick progress was possible only if the european 
community showed the political will to achieve it but she doubted 
whether negotiators could have a deal ready for signing by the end 
of the weeklong meeting which begins in brussels on dec 3 
however an american official in brussels told reporters that 
the united states has no intention of walking out of the talks 
despite the acrimonious dispute with the european community 
we want to keep at this it is important even if the 
prospects are unpromising you soldier on said the official 
who demanded anonymity 
i dont think the united states would be the first to walk 
away from the table and i think we would discourage others from 
walking away he said 
the united states has asked its trading partners to slash farm 
income supports by 75 percent and export subsidies by 90 percent 
over a 10year period starting in 1991 
the united states hopes that lowering trade barriers will enable 
its farmers to sell more goods on the world market other 
farmexporting countries like argentina and australia also would 
like a chance to export more 
the european community however contends it needs its vast 
network of agriculture supports to protect its farm community of 
some 10 million farmers many of whom have small operations 
the ec has suggested trimming subsidies on major farm crops by 
30 percent over 10 years retroactive to 1986 it has made no 
promises to reduce export subsidies 
yeutter said the europeans have already cut about half of the 
offered 30 percent reducing their actual offer to a 15 percent 
cut 
yeutter who is visiting european capitals in search of a 
compromise said he has encountered a view among europeans that the 
united states will back down on its demands 
that is a dangerous impression and one that is doomed to be 
incorrect yeutter said 
german economics minister helmut haussmann said after a meeting 
with yeutter that germany hoped the talks could proceed on 
technical questions despite the agriculture impasse but yeutter 
said the heart of the issue must be addressed 
hills said many of the 105 nations involved in the uruguay round 
will not be interested in making progress in other areas of the 
talks such as intellectual property or services if they do not 
achieve progress in the agricultural talks 
hills us secretary of states james a baker iii and commerce 
secretary robert mosbacher will travel to brussels for another set 
of talks on friday top ec officials were in washington earlier in 
the week to address the dispute 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

