<DOCNO> AP901114-0243 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a 583 million pipeline that would pump 
canadian natural gas to the northeast won federal approval 
wednesday over objections from hudson valley and connecticut 
propertyowners whose land would be crossed 
the unanimous decision by the federal energy regulatory 
commission in favor of the iroquois pipeline came after four years 
of debate among environmentalists homeowners and rival energy 
suppliers 
opponents included oil wildcatters in the southwest as well as 
psychologist dr joyce brothers whose hudson valley estate would 
be crossed by the pipeline 
but tight energy supplies in new england new york and new 
jersey apparently outweighed environmental arguments and the 
protests of domestic oil and gas suppliers 
the gas is needed in the area to be served by iroquois said 
ferc chairman martin allday it is my personal goal to get pipe 
in the ground to serve customers 
ferc board member jerry langdon said the decision would help 
move the united states toward relying on energy supplies in north 
america if not within its own borders 
canada is going to play a role in our natural gas supply in 
the future and i think that the iroquois pipeline is going to be an 
integral part of that langdon said 
supporters of the project include massachusetts gov michael s 
dukakis sen daniel patrick moynihan dny and new york gov 
mario cuomo 
the pipeline will extend 370 miles from the st lawrence river 
through the woodlands of upstate new york beneath the hudson 
river into affluent sections of western connecticut and across 
long island sound to long island iroquois officials hope to have 
gas flowing to new york and new england by november 1991 and to 
complete the line by january 1992 
its a great day said robert j reid president of the 
iroquois gas transmission system a consortium of us and canadian 
gas companies and utilities based in shelton conn it was 
imperative that we receive ferc approval in november to maintain 
our timetable for constructing the pipeline 
iroquois is designed to deliver 575 million cubic feet of gas 
daily or enough to meet the energy needs of 15 million homes 
iroquois still has regulatory hurdles to clear including permits 
from the us army corps of engineers and the department of energy 
thousands of property owners along the route have not yet agreed to 
let iroquois pay for rightofway privileges across their land 
iroquois may have to settle some of those cases in court 
a hudson valley citizens group called gasp has promised to file 
an immediate appeal with ferc and if that fails to appeal the 
decision in federal court 
domestic energy suppliers complained that iroquois will 
discourage domestic energy exploration and production and will 
compete unfairly with us pipelines and oil companies 
iroquois affiliates include connecticut natural gas corp 
brooklyn union gas co transcanada pipelines ltd and the new 
york power authority customers include long island lighting co 
boston gas co and consolidated edison co of new york 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

