southland corp which filed for bankruptcy last 
month said wednesday it lost nearly twice as much money in the 
third quarter as it did in the same period last year 
southland showed a smaller loss for the nine months that ended 
sept 30 than in the same period of 1989 however and it reported 
higher revenues 
southland owns 7eleven the nations largest convenience store 
chain 
the company lost 1225 million or 61 cents a share on revenue 
of 226 billion in the third quarter that compares to a loss of 
634 million or 33 cents a share on revenue of 223 billion in 
the same quarter a year ago 
the burden of paying off a 49 billion takeover financed with 
debt forced the company to seek chapter 11 bankruptcy protection 
last month the filing allows southland to operate under court 
supervision while it develops a plan to pay creditors 
southland submitted a prepackaged reorganization plan that 
had won approval from 90 percent of its creditors us bankruptcy 
judge harold c abramson set a dec 14 confirmation hearing for the 
plan 
on wednesday the company said it had sufficient working capital 
to maintain normal operations at its convenience stores 
distribution and food centers 
sales at comparable stores rose 11 percent during the quarter 
and 24 percent during the first nine months but gross profits 
from those sales declined in the quarter and was up only slightly 
for the nine months because there were fewer 7eleven stores 
