<TEXT>
gold futures prices tumbled wednesday on new yorks commodity 
exchange in a session marked by growing recession fears and 
reaction to white house actions concerning the situation in the 
persian gulf 
on other commodities markets silver platinum and energy 
futures prices slipped grains and soybeans prices collapsed 
cattle futures rose and pork futures were mixed 
gold settled 870 to 850 lower with december at 37850 a 
troy ounce 
gold began falling in early trading amid profittaking from 
tuesdays gains and closed sharply lower after trading was stopped 
several times by an automatically triggered mechanism activated 
when prices go below a set figure 
basically two events caused the drop said peter cardillo 
director of commodities research for jesup josephtal amp co inc in 
new york there was confusion over whether or not the federal 
reserve has eased interest rates and statements out of the white 
house suggesting they were not going to call a special session of 
congress to debate the gulf crisis 
silver and platinum prices followed gold cardillo said silver 
settled 43 cents to 34 cents lower with december at 4175 an 
ounce platinum settled 590 lower across the board with january 
at 41390 
energy futures also fell the new york mercantile exchange on 
recessionary fears and continued attention to events connected to 
the persian gulf 
light sweet crude settled 196 to 26 cents lower with december 
at 3116 a barrel heating oil settled 191 cents to 136 cents 
lower with december at 8664 cents a gallon unleaded gasoline 
settled 272 cents to 141 cents lower with december at 8039 cents 
a gallon 
grains and soybeans futures prices tumbled for the fourth 
consecutive session on the chicago board of trade as speculators 
fretted over abundant supplies and poor demand 
followthrough selling from tuesdays poor close pressured 
futures throughout the day as commercial firms cashed in in light 
of good harvesting weather in the regions where the crops are 
grown 
corn soybeans and wheat are all suffering from nearrecord 
harvests and little export demand and prices have slumped as 
speculators move to the sidelines waiting for activity 
we havent seen any things confirmed in terms of export 
activity said mark weidner an analyst for cargill investor 
services inc without confirmation or seeing shipments going out 
rumors of activity will be just that and well continue to see 
falling prices 
soybeans also have suffered from a government report issued last 
week that found a higher than expected supply of the crop than was 
previously expected 
reports of taiwans purchase of 20000 tons of the crop and talk 
that israel and mexico also may be in the market failed to slow the 
futures slide 
wheat futures settled 7 cents to 6 cents lower with december at 
255 a bushel corn futures were 6 cents to 5 cents lower with 
december at 224 a bushel oats were 5 cents to 4 cents lower 
with december at 107 a bushel soybeans were 10 cents to 5 
cents lower with november at 554 a bushel 
cattle futures prices were spurred another day by strong cash 
market sales on the chicago mercantile exchange but pork futures 
prices were mixed to lower as trade took profits on gains made this 
week 
live cattle settled 15 cent to 55 cent higher with december at 
7912 cents a pound feeder cattle was 20 cent to 80 cent higher 
with november at 8855 cents a pound hogs were 60 cent lower to 
25 cent higher with december at 5390 cents a pound frozen pork 
bellies were 102 cents to 10 cent lower with february at 7205 
cents a pound 
