bally manufacturing corp on wednesday reported a 
thirdquarter loss of 847 million and said the company missed an 
184 million payment to bondholders 
the chicagobased company said the loss of 302 per share for 
the three months ending sept 30 compared with a loss of 371 
million or 21 cents per share for the same period a year ago 
the results for the latest quarter included 91 million in 
litigation costs and a 69 million writeoff in intangible assets 
all related to a missed payment oct 15 on 18 billion in debt 
from a restructuring of ballys nevada casino subsidiary 
wednesday ended a 30day grace period for bally to make the loan 
payment said bally spokeswoman janie lewis she said the company 
was still in negotiations with our bondholders on a debt 
restructuring plan 
the thirdquarter 1989 results included an 84 million expense 
associated with the refinancing of ballys park place casino hotel 
in atlantic city 
excluding extraordinary items bally posted a net loss of 65 
million in the third quarter compared with a gain of 47 million a 
year ago 
thirdquarter revenues rose to 5313 million from 5304 
million bally said in a statement 
bally operates four casino hotels and numerous fitness centers 
across the country and also markets a line of gaming equipment of 
securities fraud at sentencing by us district judge miriam 
goldman cedarbaum 
mulheren did not address the court before sentencing he relied 
on statements by puccio who asked for leniency because mulheren 
suffered from manic depression and because of his many charitable 
acts 
the most we have here is someone who momentarily strayed and 
committed one act on one day against a lifetime of honesty and 
respectability puccio said 
cedarbaum said mulherens crimes required incarceration 
anyone who tampers with the integrity of the stock market will go 
to prison 
after sentencing mulheren to a year and one day in prison 
cedarbaum allowed him to remain free pending appeal if his 
conviction is upheld it is unlikely mulheren will serve the entire 
sentence because he will be eligible for parole after serving four 
months 
asked his reaction to the sentence mulheren said nobody 
likes to go to jail right 
prosecutors had charged that mulheren bought 75000 gulf amp 
western shares at boeskys behest driving the stock to 45 a 
share the price at which boesky wanted to sell about 35 million 
shares back to the company 
boesky the exstock speculator whose admissions led to several 
prominent indictments on wall street agreed in 1986 to plead 
guilty to one count of lying to federal investigators and pay 100 
million in fines he was released from custody in april after 
serving two years of a threeyear term 
the high point of mulherens trial came when boesky was called 
as a prosecution witness against his former business associate and 
friend boesky admitted he traded suitcases stuffed with cash for 
confidential information about imminent takeovers 
mulheren a laidback multimillionaire who often flew by 
helicopter to his trial flouted convention in court as he had in 
his wall street career during testimony mulheren wore a tennis 
shirt blue jeans and boat shoes 
in 1988 after learning boesky had implicated him mulheren was 
arrested leaving his rumson nj mansion carrying a loaded 
assault rifle police said he planned to shoot boesky 
authorities in new jersey last year dropped weapons possession 
charges mulherens lawyers blamed the incident which was not 
disclosed at the trial on his failure to take lithium prescribed 
to treat manic depression 
some criminal charges against mulheren remain because the jury 
was unable to reach a verdict on 26 additional counts of securities 
fraud mail fraud and recordkeeping violations 
cedarbaum declared a mistrial on that portion of the case and 
the government has yet to decide whether to retry mulheren on the 
pending counts 
those charges alleged mulheren parked for boesky securities 
of unocal corp warner communications inc storer communications 
inc boise cascade corp american hospital supply inc and rh 
macy amp co 
parking is the illegal practice of disguising ownership of 
securities to avoid federal reporting requirements 
mulherens codefendant leonard destefano 34 a former trader 
at mulherens defunct firm jamie securities co was acquitted of 
all conspiracy and recordkeeping violations charges brought 
against him 
