<DOCNO> AP901114-0253 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mcdonalds corp on wednesday announced it is 
test marketing a lowfat hamburger that trade groups said could 
help woo healthconscious consumers 
but nutrition experts cautioned that the efforts of mcdonalds 
and its competitors such as hardees and wendys do not mean 
fastfood has become health food 
the new hamburger called the lean deluxe boasts a 91 percent 
fatfree beef patty counting the sesame seed bun and fixings 
ketchup mustard pickles onions lettuce and tomatoes it has a 
105 percent fat content and 310 calories that compares to a 207 
percent fat content and about 410 calories in a quarter pounder 
the burger is currently being testmarketed in 54 franchises in 
the harrisburg pa area said chuck rubner a spokesman for the 
oak brook illbased company 
were excited about it and are very optimistic rubner said 
they like the taste of the product and they like the fact that 
its a lowfat alternative 
there currently are no plans to nationally market the hamburger 
the patty is composed of 90 percent lean beef 9 percent water 
and 1 percent seasonings rubner said 
among the items listed as seasonings is carrageenan a gumlike 
product used in meats and other foods to bind the ingredients 
the carrageenan which does the binding job of fat is the 
secret to the patty said mary adolf a spokeswoman for the beef 
industry council of the meat board the board funded work by auburn 
university to develop the lowfat beef and ms adolf said 
mcdonalds is the first to testmarket the technology 
hardees food systems inc earlier this year test marketed in 
four cities an 84 percent fatfree hamburger and plans to sell it 
nationally in 1991 said john merritt a spokesman for the rocky 
mountain ncbased company 
the dallasbased american heart association and the center for 
science in the public interest in washington dc said there 
currently is no other fastfood chain marketing a hamburger with as 
low a fat content as mcdonalds claims 
nutrition experts welcomed the development but cautioned that 
one new product in a menu loaded with fat and cholesterol is not a 
healthy substitute 
one has to look at a foods place in relation to the total 
diet said karen millerkovach a spokeswoman for the american 
dietetic association if you go into a restaurant order the 
fatfree burger and an extralarge order of fries then you may 
not be doing yourself any favor 
the new hamburger also does little to reduce sodium content 
said michael jacobson director of the center for science in the 
public interest 
the regular quarter pounder has 660 milligrams of sodium 
compared to 650 milligrams in the lean deluxe that level is what 
i consider a dangerously unhealthy amount he said in a telephone 
interview 
millerkovach said the lean deluxe is part of a growing health 
trend for fastfood companies like mcdonalds and wendys which 
recently introduced a grilled chicken breast sandwich 
what were seeing is a change in the fastfood menu not 
necessarily away from the oldtime fatfilled and greasy foods that 
have made fastfood companies fat and happy but to provide other 
alternatives for customers she said 
rubner noted that mcdonalds has also added lowfat milkshakes 
and yogurt whole grain cereals and switched to cooking its french 
fries in allvegetable oils instead of beef tallow 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

